The function library — pyspark dot sequel dot functions.

Most of the data work from here on calls into pyspark dot sequel dot functions. This is Spark's library of column-level functions — for strings, dates, arrays, conditionals, and aggregations. There are three rules worth internalizing.

First, import explicitly. Either import the specific names you need — col, when, sum, and so on — or alias the whole module, commonly as capital F. Either style is fine.

Second, and this is the important one — the java-virtual-machine functions beat Python user-defined functions. Every function in this library runs inside the Spark java virtual machine, and it benefits from Tungsten code generation. A Python user-defined function, by contrast, requires a serialization round-trip, per row, through a separate Python worker. That is orders of magnitude slower.

Third, watch out for builtin collisions. Sum, min, max, round, and filter all clash with Python builtins. So import them with an alias — for example, sum as underscore-sum — so that a stray sum call does not quietly hit the Python builtin instead of the Spark function.

Module four already covered select, filter, with-column, casting, sorting, and null handling. This module builds the column expressions on top of those.
